# Comparing JavaScript Frameworks

Here is a comparison of the most popular JavaScript frameworks for building web applications.

## Feature Comparison

| Feature | React | Vue | Svelte | Angular |
| --- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Virtual DOM | Yes | Yes | No | No |
| Bundle Size | Medium | Small | Tiny | Large |
| Learning Curve | Moderate | Easy | Easy | Steep |
| TypeScript | Optional | Optional | Optional | Built-in |
| SSR Support | Next.js | Nuxt | SvelteKit | Angular Universal |

## Key Differences

### React

- Component-based architecture with **JSX**
- Huge ecosystem and community
- Backed by *Meta*
- Uses a virtual DOM for efficient updates

### Vue

- Progressive framework
- Template-based with **single-file components**
- Gentle learning curve
- Great documentation

### Svelte

- Compile-time framework (no virtual DOM)
- **Smallest bundle size** among major frameworks
- Reactive by default
- Growing ecosystem

### Angular

- Full-featured framework with *batteries included*
- Uses **TypeScript** by default
- Dependency injection built in
- Best for large enterprise applications

## When to Choose What

1. Choose **React** if you need a large ecosystem and community support
2. Choose **Vue** if you want an approachable framework with great docs
3. Choose **Svelte** if performance and bundle size are critical
4. Choose **Angular** if building a large enterprise application

T> Start with the framework your team already knows. Switching costs often outweigh theoretical benefits.
